[[ファイル:Yoshimiko-jinja01s3200.jpg|thumb|250px|Haiden]]
'''Yoshimiko Shrine''' (よしみこじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Konan|Q857194|WD=Q857194|1=Konan, Shiga}}, {{ill|lt=Shiga Prefecture|Q131358|WD=Q131358|1=Shiga Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}}, and its former rank was {{ill|lt=village shrine|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}.

=== Overview ===
According to shrine tradition, a divine descent occurred in year 68 of {{ill|lt=Emperor Sujin|Q333530|WD=Q333530|1=Emperor Sujin}}, and in year 2 of {{ill|lt=Emperor Suinin|Q314850|WD=Q314850|1=Emperor Suinin}}, Yoshihiko-no-Mikoto and Yoshihime-no-Mikoto, children of Ukahiko, were enshrined before Tanikuro-no-Mimae; this is said to be the founding. It corresponds to the western shrine among the division of the shrine to east and west due to disaster in {{ill|lt=811|Q29946|WD=Q29946|1=811}} (Kōnin 2)<ref name="JAPAN-GEOGRAPHIC.TV">[https://japan-geographic.tv/shiga/konan-yoshimikojinja.html Yoshimiko Shrine, Konan City, Shiga JAPAN-GEOGRAPHIC.TV] accessed 2013-05-01</ref>. The current honden was moved from the former honden of {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Kamigamo Shrine|1=UNKNOWN}} in Kyoto in 1865 (Keiō 1), after shrine buildings were badly damaged in {{ill|lt=1864|Q7704|WD=Q7704|1=1864}} (Genji 1), and was designated a national {{ill|lt=Important Cultural Property|Q1188622|WD=Q1188622|1=Important Cultural Property (Japan)}} in {{ill|lt=1921|Q2162|WD=Q2162|1=1921}} (Taishō 10)<ref name="JAPAN-GEOGRAPHIC.TV" />. {{ill|lt=Yoshihime Shrine|Q11412752|WD=Q11412752|1=Yoshihime Shrine}} about 1 km to the south has a paired relationship as the female deity counterpart to Yoshimiko Shrine's male deity.

=== Festivals ===

* Annual festival: May 1
: * It has a paired relationship with {{ill|lt=Yoshihime Shrine|Q11412752|WD=Q11412752|1=Yoshihime Shrine}}, and mikoshi from both shrines come out on that day. This is called the "Ishibe Grand Festival."

